 aside. Though she had indispensable allies in marshaling this effort=E2=80=
=94including, crucially, Chuck Schumer, Hakeem Jeffries, and Barack Obama=
=E2=80=94Pelosi=E2=80=99s role was singular in its execution and effect. St=
arting with her seminal doubt-casting appearance on Morning Joe ( https://w=
ww.msnbc.com/morning-joe/watch/nancy-pelosi-it-s-up-to-biden-to-decide-if-h=
e-s-going-to-run-214554181531?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+S=
UBSCRIBERS+%287%2F17%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUB=
SCRIBERS+%287%2F21%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.=
io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) on July 3, Pelosi conducted a masterclas=
s in power politics as sophisticated as any I have seen in 35 years of cove=
ring this stuff. She carefully and sure-handedly balanced an extraordinary =
number of
psychic variables, emotional equities, and personal histories and agendas, =
all the while methodically and relentlessly (some would say ruthlessly) tur=
ning the screws on Biden=E2=80=94making it abundantly clear that the campai=
gn to push him off the ticket wasn=E2=80=99t going to abate and, in fact, w=
as destined to become more public, direct, and voluble (and thus more embar=
rassing to him). Indeed, more than one Democratic congressperson told me th=
at Pelosi, Schumer, Jeffries, and others were prepared, if need be, to go o=
n camera this week and call on Biden to drop out because he no longer had t=
he support of his party.

Biden was well aware ( https://www.nytimes.com/2024/07/19/us/politics/biden=
-drop-out-2024-election.html?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SU=
BSCRIBERS+%287%2F17%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBS=
CRIBERS+%287%2F21%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.i=
o&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) that Pelosi was his main adversary in his
battle to stay on the ticket, which is no surprise. My sources tell me that=
 she had spoken directly to him more than once in the past week to paint a =
picture of how things would play out if Biden refused to do what she was co=
nvinced was the right thing for his party and the country. As of Friday nig=
ht, according to CNN, Biden was seething at her ( https://www.cnn.com/2024/=
07/19/politics/democratic-defections-joe-biden/index.html?utm_campaign=3DTh=
e+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%287%2F17%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+=
Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%287%2F21%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_a=
ction&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ).

Whether that was or still is true at this hour, I don=E2=80=99t know. But I=
 will say this: Nancy Pelosi worked closely with Joe Biden for a very long =
time; they accomplished a great deal together. She respects him. She feels =
for him. She loves him. But, in the end, she put all of that aside to do wh=
at she thought was
necessary for Democrats to have any chance of preventing Donald Trump from =
retaking the White House. One dearly hopes that, in the fullness of time, B=
iden will come to see Pelosi=E2=80=99s actions through that prism and not a=
s a personal betrayal, and that whatever damage has been done to their rela=
tionship can and will be mended.

