&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a#giveaway )

IV. Kamala in the Catbird Seat

What happens next, as a formal and practical matter, is very much up in the=
 air. Among many of the Democrats regretfully but incontrovertibly convince=
d that Biden standing down was the only plausible path forward, there had b=
een a reluctance to start making concrete plans for choosing and/or ratifyi=
ng a new nominee until it was clear that he would demur. Now that he has, t=
he central choice facing the party boils down to this: coronation or compet=
ition.

Over the past three weeks, a variety of party panjandrums, including the af=
orementioned Carville=E2=80=94and, more significantly, Jim Clyburn=E2=80=94=
have floated various ideas for a sort of =E2=80=9Cmini-primary=E2=80=9D con=
sisting of a series of town hall meetings or debates among small groups of =
Democrats (with the criteria for and method of selecting that group very mu=
ch T.B.D.) around the country,
culminating with an open, contested convention in Chicago. The alternative,=
 of course, is that the party forgo all of that jiggery-pokery and rally qu=
ickly, forcefully, and decisively around Biden=E2=80=99s natural heir and c=
hosen successor, V.P. Harris.

In the hours since Biden=E2=80=99s withdrawal, the party is vibing hard tow=
ard the coronation option. But in the end, according to an array of party i=
nsiders pelting me with texts, the two potential approaches may simply coll=
apse into one: an open competition in which no one except Harris steps forw=
ard to compete. California Governor Gavin Newsom and Pennsylvania Governor =
Josh Shapiro, two of the top theoretical rivals to Harris for the nominatio=
n, have endorsed her, and while other big-name governors with their eyes on=
 the Oval Office=E2=80=94J.B. Pritzker of Illinois and Gretchen Whitmer of =
Michigan=E2=80=94have stopped short of backing the V.P. as of this writing,=
 there=E2=80=99s a strong possibility that
they and other prospective challengers will reach the conclusion that the l=
ong-term political risks of challenging her outweigh the advantages, and de=
cide to take a pass as well.

Having undertaken the unprecedented operation of replacing an incumbent com=
mander-in-chief at the top of the presidential ticket a month shy of the pa=
rty=E2=80=99s nominating convention, Democrats appear to be unusually unifi=
ed in their desire to pile in behind Harris, whose political liabilities ar=
e, to be sure, considerable and well-understood, but whose political assets=
 are equally clear and compelling. Aside from her youth, vigor, and prolifi=
c role as the Biden administration=E2=80=99s primary champion of women=E2=
=80=99s reproductive rights=E2=80=94no small credential, that, in the post-=
Dobbs era=E2=80=94Harris has run for president and been vetted by the natio=
nal press; the likelihood of undiscovered skeletons being dragged out of he=
r closet is close to nil (something that can=E2=80=99t be said definitively=
 about
any of the other extant possibilities).

In this, she arguably represents the safest vessel to carry Democrats acros=
s the viciously choppy waters ahead. She also offers a ready-made framing o=
f the fight against Trump that will excite a party beset by a lack of enthu=
siasm all throughout this presidential cycle: The Prosecutor vs. The Crimin=
al. Imagine that on a bumper sticker, and you=E2=80=99ll see the case for K=
amala in a nutshell.

