          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">What happens next, =
as a formal and practical matter, is very much up in the air. Among many of=
 the Democrats regretfully but incontrovertibly convinced that Biden standi=
ng down was the only plausible path forward, there had been a reluctance to=
 start making concrete plans for choosing and/or ratifying a new nominee un=
til it was clear that he would demur. Now that he has, the central choice f=
acing the party boils down to this: coronation or competition. <br/><br/>Ov=
er the past three weeks, a variety of party panjandrums, including the afor=
ementioned Carville=E2=80=94and, more significantly, <b>Jim Clyburn</b>=E2=
=80=94have floated various ideas for a sort of =E2=80=9Cmini-primary=E2=80=
=9D consisting of a series of town hall meetings or debates among small gro=
ups of Democrats (with the criteria for and method of selecting that group =
very much T.B.D.) around the country,
culminating with an open, contested convention in Chicago. The alternative,=
 of course, is that the party forgo all of that jiggery-pokery and rally qu=
ickly, forcefully, and decisively around Biden=E2=80=99s natural heir and c=
hosen successor, V.P. Harris.<br/><br/>In the hours since Biden=E2=80=99s w=
ithdrawal, the party is vibing <i>hard </i>toward the coronation option. Bu=
t in the end, according to an array of party insiders pelting me with texts=
, the two potential approaches may simply collapse into one: an open compet=
ition in which no one except Harris steps forward to compete. California Go=
vernor <b>Gavin Newsom</b> and Pennsylvania Governor <b>Josh Shapiro</b>, t=
wo of the top theoretical rivals to Harris for the nomination, have endorse=
d her, and while other big-name governors with their eyes on the Oval Offic=
e=E2=80=94<b>J.B. Pritzker</b> of Illinois and <b>Gretchen Whitmer </b>of M=
ichigan=E2=80=94have stopped short of backing the V.P. as of this writing, =
there=E2=80=99s a strong possibility that
they and other prospective challengers will reach the conclusion that the l=
ong-term political risks of challenging her outweigh the advantages, and de=
cide to take a pass as well.<br/><br/>Having undertaken the unprecedented o=
peration of replacing an incumbent commander-in-chief at the top of the pre=
sidential ticket a month shy of the party=E2=80=99s nominating convention, =
Democrats appear to be unusually unified in their desire to pile in behind =
Harris, whose political liabilities are, to be sure, considerable and well-=
understood, but whose political assets are equally clear and compelling. As=
ide from her youth, vigor, and prolific role as the Biden administration=E2=
=80=99s primary champion of women=E2=80=99s reproductive rights=E2=80=94no =
small credential, that, in the post-<i>Dobbs </i>era=E2=80=94Harris has run=
 for president and been vetted by the national press; the likelihood of und=
iscovered skeletons being dragged out of her closet is close to nil (someth=
ing that can=E2=80=99t be said definitively about
any of the other extant possibilities). <br/><br/>In this, she arguably rep=
resents the safest vessel to carry Democrats across the viciously choppy wa=
ters ahead. She also offers a ready-made framing of the fight against Trump=
 that will excite a party beset by a lack of enthusiasm all throughout this=
 presidential cycle: The Prosecutor vs. The Criminal. Imagine that on a bum=
per sticker, and you=E2=80=99ll see the case for Kamala in a nutshell.<br/>=
</td>
